{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476411"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:46:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:46:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13740"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13740"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.44,0.19,0.1,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6359"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55373"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6359"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13740"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40903"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2306"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11811"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16277"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16958"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55373"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother for a new rash. The rash started on his cheeks five days ago and has now spread to his arms and legs. He had an upper respiratory tract infection two weeks ago which resolved without treatment. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with normal vital signs. There is a symmetrical papular rash on his cheeks (Image), extensor surfaces of his arms and legs, and buttocks.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gianotti-Crosti syndrome","Erythema infectiosum","Erythema multiforme","Papular urticaria","Scabies"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe symmetrical papular rash in this well child, preceded by a viral illness and affecting the cheeks, extensor surfaces and buttocks, is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003EGianotti-Crosti syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. This is a self-limiting childhood exanthem that typically occurs between the ages of six months and 12 years. It is thought to be a cutaneous response to a variety of infections, most commonly viral infections such as Epstein-Barr virus, hepatitis B virus, cytomegalovirus, or coxsackievirus. The rash usually resolves spontaneously within 8-12 weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema infectiosum\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as fifth disease or slapped cheek syndrome, presents with a \u0022slapped cheek\u0022 appearance and a reticulated or lacy rash on the trunk and extremities. It is caused by parvovirus B19 infection. (image 1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema multiforme\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by target-like lesions with a central blister or crust, an inner pale ring, and an outer erythematous halo. It is often triggered by infections such as herpes simplex virus or mycoplasma pneumoniae, or medications. (image 2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPapular urticaria\u003C/strong\u003E presents with very itchy red papules and is caused by hypersensitivity to insect bites. Careful examination may reveal a central punctum at the site of the bite. (image 3)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScabies\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by the mite \u003Cem\u003ESarcoptes scabiei \u003C/em\u003Eand typically presents with intensely pruritic erythematous papules and burrows in the web spaces of the fingers, wrists, axillae and genitals. This child\u0027s distribution of rash would be atypical for scabies. (image 4)\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gianotti-Crosti syndrome is a self-limiting childhood exanthem characterised by a papular or papulovesicular rash.","The rash in Gianotti-Crosti syndrome is typically symmetrical and affects the cheeks, extensor surfaces of the extremities, and buttocks.","Gianotti-Crosti syndrome is usually preceded by a viral infection, most commonly Epstein-Barr virus, hepatitis B virus, or other viral illnesses."],"references":["Gianoti crosti new photo for diagnosis. In: Creativecommons [online]. Available at: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","Chuh A. Gianotti-Crosti syndrome (papular acrodermatitis). In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/gianotti-crosti-syndrome-papular-acrodermatitis","Oboli VN, Ebong IL, Tejada Amaro O, Regis JA, Waseem M. Gianotti-Crosti Syndrome: A Benign Dermatosis. Cureus. 2023 Jun 12;15(6):e40328. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10260319/","Gzzz, CC BY-SA 4.0 \u003Chttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0\u003E, via Wikimedia Commons","Grook Da Oger, CC BY-SA 3.0 \u003Chttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0\u003E, via Wikimedia Commons","Enochlau, CC BY-SA 3.0 \u003Chttp://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\u003E, via Wikimedia Commons","Gzzz, CC BY-SA 4.0 \u003Chttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0\u003E, via Wikimedia Commons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40903"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13740"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20672"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21089"},{"type":"media","id":"21090"},{"type":"media","id":"2109